{"type":"message","id":"e9cd626c","parentId":"3ee1ad66","timestamp":"2026-05-12T15:50:45.814Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, there's an issue with the toast - I used `len(results)` and `len(filtered)` as if they were variables in scope, but in Python, f-strings inside string literals can't access variables that way. Actually they CAN inside an f-string. But the problem is `len(results)` and `len(filtered)` are inside an f-string that gets evaluated when the file is read - they're not being written as f-string variables, they're being written as if `results` is a variable in the script. Let me fix this - the toast should reference the actual variable names that will exist in the real code.\n\nActually, in the replacement code, I wrote:\n```python\nnew_lines.append(toast_indent + 'st.toast(f\"掃描完成！ {len(results)} 檔 ({len(filtered)} 通過篩選)\", icon=\"✅\")\\n')\n```\n\nThis is INSIDE a Python script that generates code, so `len(results)` and `len(filtered)` in the f-string will be evaluated when the script runs (not when the generated code runs). Since `results` and `filtered` don't exist in the script, this will throw a NameError at script runtime.\n\nI need to escape the f-string so that `len(results)` and `len(filtered)` become part of the generated code rather than evaluated in the script. I should use double braces `{{}}` in the template to produce single braces `{}` in the output... or I should just write the line differently.\n\nActually in Python, when you write:\n```python\nf\"st.toast(f\"掃描完成！ {len(results)} 檔\", icon=\"✅\")\"\n```\n\nThis is a nested f-string problem. The outer quotes are single quotes, but the inner f-string uses double quotes. Let me rewrite properly:\n\n```python\nnew_lines.append(toast_indent + 'st.toast(\"掃描完成！ ' + str(len(results)) + ' 檔\", icon=\"✅\")\\n')\n```\n\nBut this has the same issue - `results` doesn't exist in the script. I need to use `%%results%%` as a placeholder that I can replace later, or I should generate code that uses the actual variable names but write them as string literals. Since `results` and `filtered` will actually exist in the generated streamlit code, what I should do is generate code with those variable names so they're valid when the script runs.\n\nThe problem is the script itself tries to evaluate `len(results)` before the generated code even exists. I should use string concatenation or format the placeholder differently so the template substitution happens correctly. The real issue is that I'm trying to use f-strings inside a script that's generating code, but the variables don't exist in that scope. I should write the generated code as a template string where `results` and `filtered` are actual variables in the output, not things the script tries to evaluate. So I'll write the template as a raw string that gets written to the file directly, using proper string formatting to insert the variable names without trying to evaluate them prematurely.\n","thinkingSignature":"14c8032aed9e67100db9f12c1b3b08446c6bde67ae9e941ae10a6c4ca176da89"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fufgoo7i1l5i_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import re\n\npath = r\"C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Tina_Quant_System\\streamlit_tw_stock.py\"\nwith open(path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    lines = f.readlines()\n\n# Add toast after st.success scan completion\n# Lines around 1655 (TW) and 2326 (US)\nreplacements = 0\nnew_lines = []\ni = 0\nwhile i < len(lines):\n    line = lines[i]\n    # TW toast: around line 1655\n    if 'st.success(f\"{len(results)} stocks | {len(filtered)} after filter\")' in line and i > 1550 and i < 1700:\n        indent = len(line) - len(line.lstrip())\n        new_lines.append(line)\n        new_lines.append(' ' * indent + 'st.toast(f\"掃描完成！ {len(results)} 檔 ({len(filtered)} 通過篩選)\", icon=\"✅\")\\n')\n        replacements += 1\n        i += 1\n    # US toast: around line 2326\n    elif 'st.success(f\"{len(