{"type":"message","id":"3715cb9a","parentId":"a4563fee","timestamp":"2026-05-12T15:59:57.276Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the real issue!\n\nLine 1712: `st.dataframe(` is at indent 0 (column 0)!\nThis is a HUGE problem - `st.dataframe(` at column 0 means it's at the module level, NOT inside the `if filtered:` block!\n\nThe `st.dataframe(` call should be inside the `if filtered:` block (indent 8) but it's at column 0. This makes the `)` on line 1728 close the wrong block.\n\nActually wait - Python doesn't care about horizontal alignment, it cares about the actual indentation level. Let me think about this again:\n\n- Line 1712: `st.dataframe(` at indent 0 means it's at module level\n\n\n- Line 1714 `df,` at indent 12\n- Line 1728 `)` at indent 8\n- Line 1732 `with st.expander` at indent 12\n\nSo when Python parses this, the closing paren at line 1728 is at indent 8 while the opening call at line 1712 is at indent 0, which breaks the structure. But then Python continues parsing anyway - the `with st.expander` at indent 12 would be inside some block...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the issue might be that Python is interpreting this differently than I expect. Let me trace through what happens when the parser hits line 1712 with `st.dataframe(` at column 0 - it's starting a new statement at module level, then line 1714 with `df,` at indent 12 is part of that call's arguments, but the closing `)` at indent 8 doesn't match the indentation of the opening statement. I'm realizing the indentation mismatch reveals something odd here—if `st.dataframe(` starts at column 0 but its closing `)` is at indent 8, that breaks Python's indentation rules. I think what's actually happening is that the old version of the code used `st.dataframe(df, width='stretch', height=600, hide_index=True)` without any column configuration, and when I tried to add the column config block, I somehow introduced these inconsistent indentation levels that the parser is catching. the line I replaced. In the original, the closing `)` was at 8 spaces (correct). But my new `)` is also at 8 spaces...\n\nOh wait! I think I see what happened. When my Python script added the new column_config code, it added it at the RIGHT indent levels. But the original code that was replaced (`st.dataframe(df, width='stretch', height=600, hide_index=True)`) had its `)` at 8 spaces. When I replaced just the call line, I created:\n```\nst.dataframe(\n            df,\n            column_config={\n...\n            },           ← 12 spaces (correct for dict inside funcall)\n    use_container_width=True,  ← 12 spaces (correct for kwargs) \n    hide_index=True,    ← 12 spaces (correct for kwargs)\n)                    ← 8 spaces (WRONG! should be at same level as \"st.dataframe(\" which is 0)\n```\n\nBut in Python, the `)` for a multi-line function call can be at ANY indent level - Python uses the INDENT of the first token to determine the base block. So `st.dataframe(` at column 0 means the block starts there, and the `)` at 8 spaces means \"close the block started at indent 0\". This is actually valid Python syntax!\n\nAnd then the `with st.expander` at 12 spaces would be INSIDE a `if filtered:` block at 8 spaces? No wait - if `st.dataframe(` is at column 0, it's at the top level, not inside `if filtered:`. So the `)` at 8 closes it and we're back at the `if filtered:` level (8 spaces).\n\nThe real problem is that `st.dataframe(` is at column 0 when it should be indented to match the `for r in filtered:` loop that contains it. That's why the error is flagged as \"unexpected indent\" rather than a syntax error—the parser can handle the mismatched parentheses, but the indentation level itself is wrong.\n\nI need to shift the entire `st.dataframe(` call 8 spaces to the right so it aligns with the loop it belongs to. Then the `)` will close at the same level, and the `with st.expander` statement will properly be inside the `if filtered:` block at 8 spaces.","thinkingSignature":"66036bc04fafe5e2df3ed698ca808f70034d78416bd3fb617f72bc10f8a00a77"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_l2oj9lt2tu10_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"path = r\"C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Tina_Quant_System\\streamlit_tw_stock.py\"\nwith open(path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    lines = f.readlines()\n\n# The st.dataframe call is at column 0 but should be at indent 8 (inside 'if filtered:')\n# All lines from st.dataframe to its closing ')' need to be shifted by 8 spaces\n\n# Find the st.dataframe line (should be at column 0, needs to move to 8)\nstart_idx = None\nend_idx = None\nfor i, l in enumerate(lines):\n    if 'st.dataframe(' in l and l.lstrip().startswith('st.dataframe('):\n        start_idx = i\n        print(f\"Found st.dataframe at line {i+1}, indent {len(l)-len(l.lstrip())}\")\n    if start_idx is not None and l.strip() == ')' and i > start_idx:\n        end_idx = i\n        print(f\"Found closing ) at line {i+1}, indent {len(l)-len(l.lstrip())}\")\n        break\n\n# Shift all lines from start_idx to end_idx+1 by 8 spaces\nif start_idx and end_idx:\n    for i in range(start_idx, end_idx+1):\n        lines[i] = '        ' + lines[i]  # add 8 spaces\n    \n    # Verify\n    print(\"\\nAfter fix:\")\n    for i in range(start_idx-2, end_idx+3):\n        l = lines[i]\n        indent = len(l) - len(l.lstrip())\n        print(f\"  {i+1:4d} [{indent:2d}]: {l.strip()[:70]}\")\n\nwith open(path, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    f.writelines(lines)\n\n# Verify syntax\nimport ast\nwith open(path, encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    src = f.read()\ntry:\n    ast.parse(src)\n    print(\"Syntax OK\")\nexcept SyntaxError as e:\n    print(f\"SyntaxError: line {e.lineno}: {e.msg}\")\n","path":"C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\agents\\ray\\fix_streamlit_indent.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1880,"output":1435,"cacheRead":132864,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":136179,"