{"type":"message","id":"ac0df63b","parentId":"8cecb274","timestamp":"2026-05-12T17:00:46.068Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ollama API is reachable (the /api/tags endpoint works fine) but the /api/generate endpoint is timing out. This is strange - it suggests the model is loading but taking too long to generate even a simple response.\n\nLet me check if the issue is with the Q4_K_M quantization level. IQ4_XS is a more aggressive quantization than Q4_K_M - maybe it's causing the model to be very slow at generation.\n\nWait - actually the base model is `qwen3.5-4b-iq4xs` which uses IQ4_XS quantization. When we created ray-v3.5, it also inherited the Q4_K_M quantization level from the Modelfile (as shown in the /api/tags output: `\"quantization_level\": \"Q4_K_M\"`).\n \nThe base model's more aggressive quantization might be the culprit here, but I'm also wondering if the i9-13900H with its 14 cores is just too slow for this model. The generation speed is crawling at less than 1 token per second, which would make even a short response take over a minute.\n\nLet me try using the chat API instead since it's designed for conversational interactions and might handle generation differently. Actually, looking at the logs more carefully, the model is loading successfully (the Modelfile parsing succeeded), so the issue isn't with the setup - it's genuinely just the generation speed. The Q4_K_M quantization should still be faster than Q5, so quantization isn't the problem here. With only 4GB of VRAM available and the model needing more, it's likely being swapped to system RAM, which would explain the slow generation. Let me check the actual VRAM usage to confirm this.\n","thinkingSignature":"1e377df12d4589f17f61fe30bd17bdca2a8260f3836999f897fe915e3c07635b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yjpuk1wl4ifl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"import subprocess; r=subprocess.run(['nvidia-smi','--query-gpu=memory.used,m