{"type":"message","id":"8d1aab51","parentId":"c13c5520","timestamp":"2026-05-12T17:01:48.420Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All three are still loaded. Let me try stopping them one at a time with separate commands. Actually, the issue might be that Ollama's stop command doesn't unload the model from GPU memory - it just stops the server process or removes it from the active list. And since Ollama keeps models in memory by default (they stay loaded), stopping them doesn't free VRAM.\n\nThe real issue is that with RTX 4050 (6GB VRAM), running 2x 7B models (each ~4.7GB) would require 9.4GB - way over the 6GB limit. But somehow they're there... and the 4B model is timing out.\n\n\nBut wait, the VRAM is at 4362MiB/6141MiB with 95% GPU utilization, so all three models must be loaded somehow. The timeout on the API calls is likely just Ollama's model loading taking too long when the GPU is already saturated with 7B inference at high utilization.\n\nThe real problem is that I'm trying to run two 7B models simultaneously on a 6GB card—that's physically impossible since each 7B Q4 needs ~4.7GB. The system shouldn't allow this, which makes me wonder if Ollama is spilling to RAM or if there's something else going on with how the models are actually loaded.\n\nActually, I think Ollama keeps all registered models in memory regardless of the \"stopped\" state, so the VRAM constraint is even tighter than I thought. The 4B model (2.7GB) can barely fit alongside one 7B (4.7GB) but not two. When I try to run the 4B, it likely loads on top of the existing models, causing the timeout as the system struggles to allocate and swap memory.\n\nThe solution is straightforward—I need to stop the 7B models first before running the 4B, even though the \"stop\" command doesn't actually free VRAM in Ollama's architecture. Let me test by killing the ollama.exe processes to truly free up the GPU memory.\n","thinkingSignature":"5863bc56d9ac323216455e96ed6592